This is even as health experts warned of dire consequences should Kenya fail to act in time.
Professor Omu Anzala, a virologist at the University of Nairobi, warned that the new variant is distressing even though it is normal for viruses to mutate and that new variants are bound to come up.
“Everybody is worried because this new variant is spreading faster. When viruses change, we all become worried because they can change for the better or for the worse and this should disturb us as a country.” Health Secretary Mutahi Kagwe said Kenya was monitoring events in the UK. Stakeholders are holding on to hope for the recovery of international tourism after the arrival of a first international charter flight. The National Treasury has revised the tax bands for salaried workers. Prof Magoha said no child should be denied admission because of unpaid fees for the first term or second term. The national government has not hidden its intent to control the capital city.